// Neutral evolved maximum when not in possession; used as the scale anchor for
// the tighter in-possession cap.
const DEFENSIVE_LINE_MAX_GAP_NOT_IN_POSSESSION_YARDS: f64 = 40.0;
// Offside line flatness: when defending, the back four holds a FLAT line so it presents a clean
// offside trap — the total fore-aft (along-attacking-axis) spread between the four is kept within
// this many yards (each defender within ±half of it of the line average). Eased toward level over
// the ~3s consistency window (not snapped) so a defender caught out of line jogs back into it; in
// possession the clamp lifts entirely (centre-backs split, full-backs overlap).
const BACK_FOUR_OFFSIDE_LEVEL_BAND_YARDS: f64 = 2.0;
// Six-yard-line stickiness (open play only). The back four must not retreat all the way onto
// its own end-line: in open play the 6-yard line acts as the effective end-line — a soft floor /
// non-linearity on how DEEP (close to our own goal) the back-four band TARGET may sit. Because
// this only sets the target and the line eases onto it over the ~3s consistency grace, all four
// may still be physically inside 0-6yd for under ~3s (chasing a ball, easing back out), but
// within ~3s their target pulls them back so the line AVERAGE settles on the 6-yard line. Lifted
// for dead-ball restarts that legitimately drop the line off (corners &c., where the offside law
// is suspended) and while an opponent is breaking clean through (the line must drop to cover the
// goal); the own 5-yard emergency zone is already handled by the exempt early-return.
const BACK_FOUR_SIX_YARD_LINE_FLOOR_YARDS: f64 = 6.0;
// A defender whose current position is more than this far AHEAD of the back-four band (up at the
// ball pressing or cutting a lane) has stepped out of the line, so it is excluded from the line
// centre used for the offside-flatness clamp (a cheap position test, no decision re-entry).
const LINE_STEPPED_OUT_AHEAD_YARDS: f64 = 6.0;
// Below this speed (and on the ground) the ball counts as "settled" for the shared 2yd floor.
const DEFENSIVE_LINE_SETTLED_BALL_SPEED_YPS: f64 = 6.0;
// The cushion behind the ball MUST shrink as the ball nears the defenders' OWN goal -- you
// cannot sit 20yd behind a ball that is only 18yd from your own line (that puts the line in
// the net). The cap on the gap is (ball distance from own goal) − SAFETY, so it reaches the
// 3yd floor exactly when the ball arrives at the 18yd box (18 − 15 = 3) and relaxes back to
// the full nominal cushion as the ball moves upfield. Floored at 3yd, never negative.
const DEFENSIVE_LINE_GOAL_SHRINK_SAFETY_YARDS: f64 = 15.0;
const DEFENSIVE_LINE_GAP_FLOOR_YARDS: f64 = 3.0;
// Back-four STRUCTURE (off-ball, the defender allowed to step out to engage excepted): the
// four stay a compact, FLAT, ball-side block. Laterally they occupy ~4 of the 12 lanes
// (a ~26yd block ≈ 3.9 lanes), the block's centre tracking the ball's x (shift-and-cover,
// retaining some centrality). Fore-aft they FLATTEN to the line's average depth (no
// 20-35yd stagger among the four). Both are bounded pulls toward the slot, not hard snaps.
// Back-four width and horizontal gap thresholds live in `tunables().defensive_shape`.
const BACK_FOUR_BALL_SIDE_SHIFT: f64 = 0.6;
const BACK_FOUR_LATERAL_GAIN: f64 = 0.78;
const BACK_FOUR_FLATTEN_GAIN: f64 = 0.5;
// Defending in our OWN half we tighten to a true offside-trap line: strive for the SAME
// fore-aft depth (near-full flatten), not merely a reduced stagger. Still a bounded pull
// converging over the 3s consistency horizon (eventual consistency), never a snap. On
// offense the flat line is dropped entirely (a wingback may overlap, the four may stagger).
const BACK_FOUR_OFFSIDE_TRAP_FLATTEN_GAIN: f64 = 0.9;
const BACK_FOUR_HORIZONTAL_CONSISTENCY_TARGET_SECONDS: f64 = 3.0;
// Wingback defensive pinch horizon/margin live in `tunables().defensive_shape`.
const SIX_YARD_BOX_POST_EXTENSION_YARDS: f64 = 6.0;
const SHAPE_CONSISTENCY_CLOSE_BALL_YARDS: f64 = 18.0;
const SHAPE_CONSISTENCY_FAR_BALL_YARDS: f64 = 58.0;
const SHAPE_CONSISTENCY_CLOSE_SECONDS: f64 = 1.0;
const SHAPE_CONSISTENCY_FAR_SECONDS: f64 = 5.0;
// Back-four resync grace: the far-ball horizon ceiling (s) and the per-tick easing-gain floor
// for pulling the back four back into shape. The longer ceiling + lower floor (vs the shared
// 5s / 0.75) give the line a gentle, renewable ~7s window to ease back when the ball is far,
// while a close ball still snaps it level. See `defensive_line_resync_consistency_gain`.
const BACK_FOUR_RESYNC_GRACE_SECONDS: f64 = 7.0;
const BACK_FOUR_RESYNC_GAIN_FLOOR: f64 = 0.40;
// The back-four line anchors to where the ball is HEADED, not just where it is now:
// project the ball forward by this many seconds (position + velocity + accel + jerk)
// and never sit more than the not-in-possession max gap behind that predicted point.
const DEFENSIVE_LINE_BALL_LOOKAHEAD_SECONDS: f64 = 4.0;
// Kinematic extrapolation (accel/jerk t² / t³ terms) diverges fast, so cap the total
// projected displacement — a line anchors to a plausible destination, not a runaway.
const BALL_PREDICTION_MAX_DISPLACEMENT_YARDS: f64 = 32.0;
// Midfield line sits IN FRONT of the back four by a gap that depends on the midfield's own
// length-wise pitch position: a wider 15-30yd band through the central 3/5 of the pitch, tapering
// to a compact 10-15yd band in the outer 1/5 at each end. The taper is linear across the 1/5
// boundary so the rule is continuous, not a step.
const MIDFIELD_BAND_MIDDLE_MIN_YARDS: f64 = 15.0;
const MIDFIELD_BAND_MIDDLE_MAX_YARDS: f64 = 30.0;
const MIDFIELD_BAND_END_MIN_YARDS: f64 = 10.0;
const MIDFIELD_BAND_END_MAX_YARDS: f64 = 15.0;
// While the ball is in transit (a pass / shot / loose ball), an off-ball player who has no chance
// of receiving it should get GOALSIDE of where the ball will be at the next anticipated
// possession — not just goalside of where it is now. "No chance" is approximated by being further
// than this from the anticipated point; goalside keeps the target this far on the own-goal side.
const GOALSIDE_BALL_TRANSIT_MIN_SPEED_YPS: f64 = 3.0;
const GOALSIDE_RECEIVE_CHANCE_RADIUS_YARDS: f64 = 10.0;
const GOALSIDE_MARGIN_YARDS: f64 = 1.5;
const MATCH_RESULT_LOSS_PLAYER_PENALTY: f64 = 18.0;
const MATCH_RESULT_MARGIN_REWARD_PER_GOAL: f64 = 6.0;
const MATCH_RESULT_MARGIN_PENALTY_PER_GOAL: f64 = 4.0;
const DEFENSIVE_GOAL_HISTORY_ACTIONS: usize = 50;
const DEFENSIVE_GOAL_HISTORY_MAX_PENALTY: f64 = 0.075;
const DEFENSIVE_GOAL_HISTORY_MIN_PENALTY: f64 = 0.014;
/// Hard ceiling on the deferred reward-transition backlog. Retroactive penalties
/// (turnovers, conceded goals) and reward-only ticks push onto this buffer; it is
/// drained at most `policy_train_max_transitions_per_tick` per learning-due tick,
/// so a turnover-heavy scrum can out-pace the drain. Capping the backlog (oldest
/// dropped first) bounds memory regardless of the inflow/drain imbalance.
const MAX_DEFERRED_REWARD_TRANSITIONS: usize = 4096;
/// How long a manual drag-and-drop coaching position hint steers a player before
/// it expires and the AI resumes its own positioning.
const COACH_POSITION_HINT_LIFETIME_SECONDS: f64 = 12.0;
/// Once the dragged player is within this distance of the hinted spot the hint is
/// considered satisfied and released (they've arrived).
const COACH_POSITION_HINT_ARRIVAL_YARDS: f64 = 1.5;
const DEFENSIVE_RELAXATION_THREAT_YARDS: f64 = 48.0;
const NO_PRESSURE_BACK_PASS_THRESHOLD_YARDS: f64 = 10.0;
const SETTLED_POSSESSION_SECONDS: f64 = 5.0;
// Inter-player off-ball spacing band, measured as EUCLIDEAN (straight-line) distance
// to the nearest teammate — NOT the x-axis gap (the candidate scorer reads
// `nearest_teammate_distance = sqrt(dx^2 + dy^2)`). MIN is the FLOOR (penalised below
// it for packing too tight); MAX is the "too isolated" ceiling (above it the scorer
// penalises and pulls the player back toward teammates), peaking at IDEAL between.
// User (2026-06-18) wanted "keep ~5yd between players" — that is the MIN floor, NOT a
// ceiling: capping ATTACK MAX at 10 forbade legitimate width (wingers, runners in
// behind sit 12-18yd off the nearest teammate) and collapsed the attacking shape onto
// the ball. So ATTACK keeps the 5yd floor but stretches (ideal 10, isolate-past 17);
// DEFENDING stays compact (5/7/10). The back four's own LATERAL band (1.5-8yd along x,
// adjacent pairs) is a separate, tighter rule for the defensive line.
// On offense the team STRETCHES the pitch: a wider "happy" separation band so players hold
// real distance between them (instead of bunching), rewarded up to the ideal and only pulled
// back in past the max. Defending stays compact (below).
const ATTACK_SPACING_MIN_YARDS: f64 = 7.0;
const ATTACK_SPACING_IDEAL_YARDS: f64 = 15.0;
const ATTACK_SPACING_MAX_YARDS: f64 = 24.0;
const DEFENSE_SPACING_MIN_YARDS: f64 = 5.0;
const DEFENSE_SPACING_IDEAL_YARDS: f64 = 7.0;
const DEFENSE_SPACING_MAX_YARDS: f64 = 10.0;
// How much of the opponent's lateral stretch the defending block tracks. At 0.50 the
// block sat at roughly HALF the attack's width, abandoning the far flank and collapsing
// 22 players into a central "bunchball" vacuum. A defending team narrows ball-side but
// must still honour the width of the pitch (track a stretched opponent and stay near home
// lanes), so it tracks most of the opponent's spread, not half of it.
const DEFENSE_SPREAD_FOLLOW_RATIO: f64 = 0.80;
// Territory discipline ("cover ground"). Two teammates packed into the same few yards
// add no attacking or defensive value, so beyond a brief grace window — long enough
// for a legitimate handoff, screen/block, or double-team — one of the pair is told to
// move and spreads back toward its formation slot (an LP-anchored nudge). The grace
// scales with how tight the cluster is: the closer the pair, the sooner one must peel
// off. Both clocks run continuously and reset the instant the pair separates.
//   within NEAR radius  -> NEAR grace
//   within FAR radius   -> FAR grace
// Same-team field spacing is a live football rule: stay out of the 4yd no-go
// band unless both players are actually inside an 18-yard box. The warning band
// then fades smoothly through 5/6/7yd instead of creating a hard stop.
const TEAMMATE_SPACING_NEAR_RADIUS_YARDS: f64 = 4.0;
const TEAMMATE_SPACING_FAR_RADIUS_YARDS: f64 = 8.0;
const TEAMMATE_SPACING_BOX_RADIUS_REDUCTION_YARDS: f64 = 2.0;
const TEAMMATE_SPACING_NEAR_GRACE_SECONDS: f64 = 2.0;
const TEAMMATE_SPACING_FAR_GRACE_SECONDS: f64 = 2.0;
const TEAMMATE_SPACING_CONSISTENCY_SECONDS: f64 = 2.0;
const TEAMMATE_SPACING_PATH_SAMPLES: usize = 4;
const TEAMMATE_SPACING_PATH_RELIEF_MARGIN_YARDS: f64 = 0.10;
const TEAMMATE_SPACING_PATH_RELIEF_ITERATIONS: usize = 3;
// The yielding player is encouraged out to just beyond the minimum spacing so it
// actually clears the radius instead of hovering exactly on its edge.
const TEAMMATE_SPACING_SEPARATION_MARGIN_YARDS: f64 = 0.75;
// The territory correction is a soft nudge, never a takeover: the flagged player keeps
// making its own movement decision and we only bias the decided target outward — by at
// most this fraction of the remaining spacing deficit, capped to this many yards per
// tick — so it drifts back out of the teammate's space over a few ticks rather than
// being snapped to a computed spot.
const TEAMMATE_SPACING_NUDGE_BIAS: f64 = 0.75;
const TEAMMATE_SPACING_MAX_NUDGE_YARDS: f64 = 2.2;
// Hysteresis: when a pair separates, its proximity clock DECAYS at this multiple of real
// time rather than snapping to zero, so a pair that merely orbits at the edge of the
// radius (dipping in and out) still accumulates toward the grace and gets told to spread.
// A clean, sustained break still clears it within a second or so. (The minimum-spacing
// rule is a strong one and should be honored, not dodged by momentary separations.)
const TEAMMATE_SPACING_CLOCK_DECAY_RATE: f64 = 1.0;

// Relational shape ("cover ground as a cohesive unit"). Every outfield player has an
// ideal position *relative to its formation neighbours* — derived from the base
// formation, so the difference of two players' home slots IS their ideal relative
// offset (this reproduces "left CB a few yards left of right CB", "midfielders ahead of
// defenders", "strikers ahead of midfielders", and every other pair, with no hand-coded
// matrix). Holding those offsets against the neighbours' *current* positions lets the
// whole block slide up and down the pitch together. This is a statistical proclivity,
// never a hard rule: within a tolerance band the player is left alone, and beyond it the
// proclivity is expressed three ways — a bounded positional nudge, a blend into the
// formation-LP anchor, and an MDP/POMDP shaping reward.
//
// A player's structural neighbours are the teammates whose home slots are nearest its
// own (its line partners and the adjacent lines).
const RELATIONAL_SHAPE_NEIGHBORS: usize = 4;
// Within this slack of the ideal relative offset the shape is "good enough" — no nudge,
// no penalty. Roughly the half-width of the bands in the spec (2–6, 3–8, 3–10 …).
const RELATIONAL_SHAPE_TOLERANCE_YARDS: f64 = 2.25;
// Bounded nudge toward the relationally-implied position: close this fraction of the
// out-of-band error per tick, capped to this many yards. Tuned UP from 0.5/1.25: a
// player that has drifted out of shape is pulled back toward its slot harder and faster
// (the team holds its formation more tightly) while still keeping its own decision.
const RELATIONAL_SHAPE_NUDGE_BIAS: f64 = 0.72;
const RELATIONAL_SHAPE_MAX_NUDGE_YARDS: f64 = 2.6;
// How strongly the formation-LP anchor is pulled toward the relational position (0 =
// ignore, 1 = replace) at full out-of-band error. Small: the LP keeps owning the slot,
// this only tilts a drifting player back toward relative-offset compliance. The pull
// ramps from zero (in shape) to this cap as the out-of-band error reaches
// `RELATIONAL_SHAPE_LP_ANCHOR_FULL_ERROR_YARDS`.
const RELATIONAL_SHAPE_LP_ANCHOR_WEIGHT: f64 = 0.26;
const RELATIONAL_SHAPE_LP_ANCHOR_FULL_ERROR_YARDS: f64 = 8.0;
// The LP re-anchoring only engages for a *genuinely* drifted player — the out-of-band
// error must exceed this deadzone before the slot is tilted. Below it the gentle nudge
// (#1) and shaping reward (#3) own the small corrections, and an in-shape block's solved
// targets are left exactly as they were (full ball-responsiveness, no perturbation).
const RELATIONAL_SHAPE_LP_ANCHOR_DEADZONE_YARDS: f64 = 5.0;
// MDP/POMDP shaping: potential-based reward (points per yard the player closes its
// out-of-band relational error across the decision interval). Potential-based so it
// shapes the *proclivity* without changing the optimal policy, and it is exactly zero
// when the player holds station. The error is capped so a single big swing cannot
// dominate the return.
const RELATIONAL_SHAPE_REWARD_PER_YARD: f64 = 0.025;
const RELATIONAL_SHAPE_REWARD_CAP_YARDS: f64 = 12.0;

/// All tunable distances, times, and weights for the territory-spacing and relational-
/// shape proclivities, gathered into one **configurable + learnable** bundle. It lives on
/// [`MatchConfig`] (so it can be set per match or live via the reset/config API) and —
/// because `MatchConfig` is embedded in the exported [`SoccerSelfPlayLearnedParams`] —
/// travels with the trained policy, so the self-play / evolution loop can tune these the
/// same way it tunes [`SoccerTacticalLearningWeights`]. The constants above are the
/// defaults; nothing in the engine reads them directly except this `Default`.
#[derive(Clone, Copy, Debug, PartialEq, Serialize, Deserialize)]
#[serde(rename_all = "camelCase", default)]
pub struct SoccerSpacingParams {
    // Territory spacing.
    pub near_radius_yards: f64,
    pub far_radius_yards: f64,
    pub box_radius_reduction_yards: f64,
    pub near_grace_seconds: f64,
    pub far_grace_seconds: f64,
    pub separation_margin_yards: f64,
    pub nudge_bias: f64,
    pub max_nudge_yards: f64,
    pub clock_decay_rate: f64,
    // Relational shape.
    pub relational_neighbors: usize,
    pub relational_tolerance_yards: f64,
    pub relational_nudge_bias: f64,
    pub relational_max_nudge_yards: f64,
    pub relational_lp_anchor_weight: f64,
    pub relational_lp_anchor_full_error_yards: f64,
    pub relational_lp_anchor_deadzone_yards: f64,
    pub relational_reward_per_yard: f64,
    pub relational_reward_cap_yards: f64,
}

impl Default for SoccerSpacingParams {
    fn default() -> Self {
        SoccerSpacingParams {
            near_radius_yards: TEAMMATE_SPACING_NEAR_RADIUS_YARDS,
            far_radius_yards: TEAMMATE_SPACING_FAR_RADIUS_YARDS,
            box_radius_reduction_yards: TEAMMATE_SPACING_BOX_RADIUS_REDUCTION_YARDS,
            near_grace_seconds: TEAMMATE_SPACING_NEAR_GRACE_SECONDS,
            far_grace_seconds: TEAMMATE_SPACING_FAR_GRACE_SECONDS,
            separation_margin_yards: TEAMMATE_SPACING_SEPARATION_MARGIN_YARDS,
            nudge_bias: TEAMMATE_SPACING_NUDGE_BIAS,
            max_nudge_yards: TEAMMATE_SPACING_MAX_NUDGE_YARDS,
            clock_decay_rate: TEAMMATE_SPACING_CLOCK_DECAY_RATE,
            relational_neighbors: RELATIONAL_SHAPE_NEIGHBORS,
            relational_tolerance_yards: RELATIONAL_SHAPE_TOLERANCE_YARDS,
            relational_nudge_bias: RELATIONAL_SHAPE_NUDGE_BIAS,
            relational_max_nudge_yards: RELATIONAL_SHAPE_MAX_NUDGE_YARDS,
            relational_lp_anchor_weight: RELATIONAL_SHAPE_LP_ANCHOR_WEIGHT,
            relational_lp_anchor_full_error_yards: RELATIONAL_SHAPE_LP_ANCHOR_FULL_ERROR_YARDS,
            relational_lp_anchor_deadzone_yards: RELATIONAL_SHAPE_LP_ANCHOR_DEADZONE_YARDS,
            relational_reward_per_yard: RELATIONAL_SHAPE_REWARD_PER_YARD,
            relational_reward_cap_yards: RELATIONAL_SHAPE_REWARD_CAP_YARDS,
        }
    }
}

impl SoccerSpacingParams {
    /// Sanitize into bounds so a learned/evolved/hand-set value can never produce NaN
    /// geometry, a negative radius, or a runaway nudge. Clamps in place rather than
    /// rejecting so the learning loop can push values freely and still get sane play.
    fn sanitized(mut self) -> Self {
        let yards = |v: f64, default: f64, hi: f64| {
            if v.is_finite() {
                v.clamp(0.0, hi)
            } else {
                default
            }
        };
        let frac = |v: f64, default: f64, hi: f64| {
            if v.is_finite() {
                v.clamp(0.0, hi)
            } else {
                default
            }
        };
        let d = SoccerSpacingParams::default();
        self.near_radius_yards = yards(self.near_radius_yards, d.near_radius_yards, 40.0);
        self.far_radius_yards =
            yards(self.far_radius_yards, d.far_radius_yards, 40.0).max(self.near_radius_yards);
        self.box_radius_reduction_yards = yards(
            self.box_radius_reduction_yards,
            d.box_radius_reduction_yards,
            40.0,
        );
        self.near_grace_seconds = yards(self.near_grace_seconds, d.near_grace_seconds, 120.0);
        self.far_grace_seconds = yards(self.far_grace_seconds, d.far_grace_seconds, 120.0);
        self.separation_margin_yards = yards(
            self.separation_margin_yards,
            d.separation_margin_yards,
            20.0,
        );
        self.nudge_bias = frac(self.nudge_bias, d.nudge_bias, 1.0);
        self.max_nudge_yards = yards(self.max_nudge_yards, d.max_nudge_yards, 20.0);
        self.clock_decay_rate = frac(self.clock_decay_rate, d.clock_decay_rate, 100.0);
        self.relational_neighbors = self.relational_neighbors.clamp(1, 10);
        self.relational_tolerance_yards = yards(
            self.relational_tolerance_yards,
            d.relational_tolerance_yards,
            60.0,
        );
        self.relational_nudge_bias = frac(self.relational_nudge_bias, d.relational_nudge_bias, 1.0);
        self.relational_max_nudge_yards = yards(
            self.relational_max_nudge_yards,
            d.relational_max_nudge_yards,
            20.0,
        );
        self.relational_lp_anchor_weight = frac(
            self.relational_lp_anchor_weight,
            d.relational_lp_anchor_weight,
            1.0,
        );
        self.relational_lp_anchor_full_error_yards = yards(
            self.relational_lp_anchor_full_error_yards,
            d.relational_lp_anchor_full_error_yards,
            60.0,
        )
        .max(1e-3);
        self.relational_lp_anchor_deadzone_yards = yards(
            self.relational_lp_anchor_deadzone_yards,
            d.relational_lp_anchor_deadzone_yards,
            60.0,
        );
        self.relational_reward_per_yard = frac(
            self.relational_reward_per_yard,
            d.relational_reward_per_yard,
            5.0,
        );
        self.relational_reward_cap_yards = yards(
            self.relational_reward_cap_yards,
            d.relational_reward_cap_yards,
            120.0,
        )
        .max(0.0);
        self
    }

    fn validate(&self) -> Result<(), String> {
        for (name, value) in [
            ("nearRadiusYards", self.near_radius_yards),
            ("farRadiusYards", self.far_radius_yards),
            ("boxRadiusReductionYards", self.box_radius_reduction_yards),
            ("nearGraceSeconds", self.near_grace_seconds),
            ("farGraceSeconds", self.far_grace_seconds),
            ("separationMarginYards", self.separation_margin_yards),
            ("nudgeBias", self.nudge_bias),
            ("maxNudgeYards", self.max_nudge_yards),
            ("clockDecayRate", self.clock_decay_rate),
            ("relationalToleranceYards", self.relational_tolerance_yards),
            ("relationalNudgeBias", self.relational_nudge_bias),
            ("relationalMaxNudgeYards", self.relational_max_nudge_yards),
            ("relationalLpAnchorWeight", self.relational_lp_anchor_weight),
            (
                "relationalLpAnchorFullErrorYards",
                self.relational_lp_anchor_full_error_yards,
            ),
            (
                "relationalLpAnchorDeadzoneYards",
                self.relational_lp_anchor_deadzone_yards,
            ),
            ("relationalRewardPerYard", self.relational_reward_per_yard),
            ("relationalRewardCapYards", self.relational_reward_cap_yards),
        ] {
            if !value.is_finite() {
                return Err(format!("spacing.{name} must be finite"));
            }
            if value < 0.0 {
                return Err(format!("spacing.{name} must be non-negative"));
            }
        }
        if self.relational_neighbors == 0 {
            return Err("spacing.relationalNeighbors must be at least 1".to_string());
        }
        if self.far_radius_yards < self.near_radius_yards {
            return Err("spacing.farRadiusYards must be >= nearRadiusYards".to_string());
        }
        Ok(())
    }
}

fn default_spacing_params() -> SoccerSpacingParams {
    SoccerSpacingParams::default()
}

const VERTICAL_LANE_COUNT: usize = PITCH_FINE_GRID_COLUMNS;
const TEAMMATE_OCCUPIED_SPACE_RADIUS_YARDS: f64 = 7.0;
const TEAMMATE_OCCUPIED_SPACE_HARD_RADIUS_YARDS: f64 = 4.0;
const TEAMMATE_OCCUPIED_SPACE_MAX_PENALTY: f64 = 28.0;
// Ball-carrier driving-lane keep-out. When a teammate is carrying the ball and
// driving forward UNPRESSURED, off-ball teammates must not run into the narrow
// corridor directly ahead of the carrier — that clogs the dribble and burns the
// space the carrier is attacking. The corridor runs `LENGTH` yds ahead of the
// carrier along its driving line, `HALF_WIDTH` yds to either side; an off-ball
// target inside it is nudged sideways out to the corridor edge (same depth).
// Suppressed when the carrier IS under pressure (a defender within
// `PRESSURE_RELIEF_DISTANCE`): then a teammate dropping into that lane to offer a
// short outlet is exactly what's wanted.
const CARRIER_LANE_KEEPOUT_LENGTH_YARDS: f64 = 12.0;
const CARRIER_LANE_KEEPOUT_HALF_WIDTH_YARDS: f64 = 2.5;
const CARRIER_LANE_KEEPOUT_PRESSURE_RELIEF_DISTANCE_YARDS: f64 = 4.5;
// Defensive goal-side recovery. When the opponent has possession — INCLUDING while
// their pass is in flight (no holder; `possession_team` falls back to last-touch) —
// every non-pressing defender/midfielder must be on the own-goal side of the ball,
// i.e. on the segment between the ball and our own goal. Strikers/forwards are
// exempt so the outlet line can stay high. An off-ball target that sits
// upfield of the ball (between ball and the opponent goal) is pulled back in y
// until it is at least `MIN` yds goal-side. Lateral offset is preserved so the
// back line keeps its width. The nearest outfielder to the ball (the primary
// presser) is exempt — someone still closes the ball down. The goal-side margin
// lives in `tunables().defensive_shape.defensive_goal_side_min_yards`.
// Position-swap / cross-through guard. Players "switching positions" and "running
// past each other" is an artefact: off the ball a player should never steer a
// straight line that carries it PAST a teammate (ending up on the far side of
// them). The guard tests the path from the player's current position to its
// movement target: if that path passes within `CORRIDOR_HALF_WIDTH` of a teammate
// AND the target lies `BEYOND_MARGIN` yds beyond that teammate along the travel
// direction (a genuine swap, not merely arriving alongside), the target is
// truncated to stop `STOP_SHORT` yds short of the nearest such teammate — never
// going backward. Only fires for moves longer than `MIN_TRAVEL`; the teammate
// must be at least `MIN_AHEAD` yds up the path to count as "in the way".
//
// Legitimate exceptions are exempt, matching real football: a man-marking /
// tracking run (its target lands within `MARK_RADIUS` of an opponent), a quick
// exchange tight to the ball (the player or its target is within
// `BALL_EXCHANGE` of the ball — handoffs and give-and-gos), running past the
// ball carrier itself, and roaming set-piece movement (the caller's `roam` flag).
const CROSS_THROUGH_MIN_TRAVEL_YARDS: f64 = 1.5;
const CROSS_THROUGH_CORRIDOR_HALF_WIDTH_YARDS: f64 = 2.0;
const CROSS_THROUGH_MIN_AHEAD_YARDS: f64 = 1.0;
const CROSS_THROUGH_BEYOND_MARGIN_YARDS: f64 = 1.0;
const CROSS_THROUGH_STOP_SHORT_YARDS: f64 = 2.5;
const CROSS_THROUGH_MARK_RADIUS_YARDS: f64 = 3.0;
const CROSS_THROUGH_BALL_EXCHANGE_YARDS: f64 = 6.0;
